  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This 2024 research dataset, deposited on the NCCR MARVEL Materials Cloud platform by a collaborative team from Utrecht University and the Institut Catal\u00e0 de Nanoci\u00e8ncia i Nanotecnologia, provides the computational inputs and outputs underpinning a density functional Bogoliubov-de Gennes (DFT-BdG) implementation within the SIESTA code. While still in the early stages of accumulating citations, the dataset has registered ten online mentions and is formally linked to seven associated articles and software resources, signalling meaningful integration into an active methodological research program.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset serves as the reproducibility record for a significant methodological advance: the implementation of Bogoliubov-de Gennes theory within a density functional theory framework, specifically in the widely used SIESTA code. This combination allows first-principles calculations of superconducting properties using localized basis sets, an approach particularly suited to large or low-symmetry systems where plane-wave methods become computationally prohibitive. The primary associated publication appeared in Physical Review B, with a preprint also made available on arXiv, situating the work within the high-visibility literature of condensed matter physics and computational materials science.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The reuse graph is one of the dataset's clearest strengths at this stage. Seven downstream associations have been recorded through DataCite, connecting this deposit to the companion journal article, the preprint, foundational SIESTA methodology papers, and the SIESTA software ecosystem itself \u2014 including the AiiDA plugin for workflow automation. This web of relationships reflects a deliberate, well-structured open science practice: the dataset does not stand alone but is embedded in a broader infrastructure of tools, documentation, and prior literature that potential users can follow to reproduce or extend the calculations.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The authorship spans two institutions \u2014 Utrecht University and the Institut Catal\u00e0 de Nanoci\u00e8ncia i Nanotecnologia \u2014 representing a sustained European collaboration in computational quantum materials. Pablo Ordej\u00f3n, a principal architect of the SIESTA code, is among the co-authors, lending the implementation particular credibility within the community of users and developers already familiar with the SIESTA ecosystem. The deposit is openly accessible under a green open access model, consistent with the NCCR MARVEL platform's commitment to FAIR data principles.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Formal citation counts remain at zero at this time, which is not unusual for a specialized computational dataset in the period immediately following publication. The ten online mentions indicate that the work is circulating within relevant communities, and the absence of scite-tracked supporting or contradicting claims simply reflects the dataset's early stage in the scholarly record rather than any controversy or limitation. As the DFT-BdG methodology matures and more groups adopt or benchmark against this implementation, both the dataset and its companion article can be expected to accumulate more substantive engagement from the superconductivity and computational physics communities.</p>",
